<b>Alison Cornyn, Principal, Picture Projects</b>, will design the website, mobile app, and digital media elements for the traveling exhibit.  Cornyn has rich experience developing sensitive pubic projects on criminal justice issues, including 360 Degrees:  Perspectives on the Criminal Justice System (<a href="http://www.360degrees.org"><span style="font-weight: 400;">www.360degrees.org</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">) and the Prison Public Memory Project.  Picture Projects were the designers of the Guantánamo Public Memory Project, the pilot for the Humanities Action Lab, for which Cornyn created a template for student contributions, assembled the 13 student pieces into an engaging, cohesive exhibit worthy of major museums and community centers alike and developed a rich digital dialogue platform at </span><a href="http://www.gitmomemory.org"><span style="font-weight: 400;">www.gitmomemory.org</span></a>.

<b>Chris Dwyer, Senior Vice President at RMC Research</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, will oversee the project’s evaluation. Her experience includes program and policy research and evaluation, and translation of research into practical products for use in training and technical assistance. </span>

<b>Sandra Wheeler, Founding Partner and Co-Director at Matter Architecture Practice</b>, is the co-creative director of the project, overseeing the design and production of the physical exhibit and engagement strategies. Matter Architecture Practice’s work encompasses architecture, exhibition design, installations, custom furnishings, and projects for civic engagement within the public environment.
<h1>Consultants</h1>
<b></b><b>Piper Anderson, Chief Creative Strategist &amp; Founder at Create Forward</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, has facilitated community cultural programs in detention facilities and communities in over 26 cities, primarily between university students and incarcerated people, generating dialogue and creative action on the impact of mass incarceration on communities of color. Anderson will help design face-to-face facilitated dialogues and train facilitators </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">from each local site</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">through a dialogue “kit,” webinars, and monitored practice dialogues.</span>

<b>Sarah Pharaon,</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> </span><b>Senior Director of Methodology and Practice,</b> <b>International Coalition of Sites of Conscience</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, will bring her experience designing history-based public dialogues on sensitive issues at museums across the US, including an emerging program for prison and law enforcement museums, to review the project’s dialogue “kits” and facilitation training programs.  </span>

<b>Tricia Way, Associate Director for Research and Advancement, Inside-Out Prison Exchange Program</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, will bring her experience training faculty around the country to work in prisons and running public dialogue programs in prisons to consult on dialogue designs and facilitation training. </span>

<b>Ellen Noonan, Project Director, American Social History Project</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, is a historian and media producer.  She received her Ph.D. in U.S. History from New York University (where she is an Adjunct Instructor of Public History) and is Project Director for ASHP/CML’s New York City Teaching American History programs.  Ellen will work with </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Facing History and Ourselves</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> consultants to develop educational resources and training for high school teachers.</span>

<b>Peter Nelson, Director New York Offices at Facing History and Ourselves: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Peter has 22 years’ experience at FHAO, an organization created by educators that provides training, professional development, and resources that support the practical needs, and the spirits, of educators worldwide who share the goal of creating a better, more informed, and more thoughtful society. Peter will participate in planning, reviewing drafts of educational resources and training, and helping to promote them through the FHAO network. </span>

